{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626680"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17089"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17089"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0,0.07,0.03,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9779"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63362"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5123"},{"type":"tags","id":"10125"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26657"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a four month history of episodes of diarrhoea and flushing. She is diagnosed with a carcinoid tumour of the small intestine. Whilst definitive treatment is being planned, she is prescribed a long-acting somatostatin analogue to control her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of these agents?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binds to somatostatin receptors to inhibit hormone secretion","Stimulates dopamine release from the hypothalamus","Blocks hormone receptors on target tissues","Increases breakdown of hormones in circulation","Competes with hormones for binding to carrier proteins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESomatostatin analogues work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to somatostatin receptors to inhibit hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E from various endocrine cells. In carcinoid tumours, this reduces the release of serotonin and other vasoactive substances that cause symptoms like diarrhoea and flushing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating dopamine release from the hypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E does not represent the mechanism of action, although dopamine can have some hormone-inhibiting effects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking hormone receptors on target tissues\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as somatostatin analogues work by preventing hormone release rather than blocking their effects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing breakdown of hormones in circulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism, as these drugs act by preventing hormone release rather than affecting metabolism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompeting with hormones for binding to carrier proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as somatostatin analogues do not interact with transport proteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon somatostatin analogues include octreotide and lanreotide, which have longer half-lives than natural somatostatin. They are used to treat conditions such as acromegaly and neuroendocrine tumours by suppressing excess hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Somatostatin analogues bind to somatostatin receptors to inhibit hormone secretion from endocrine cells.","Octreotide and lanreotide are synthetic somatostatin analogues with longer half-lives than natural somatostatin.","Somatostatin analogues are used to treat neuroendocrine tumours and acromegaly by suppressing hormone production."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63362"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17089"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63362"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T17:30:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T17:31:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9779"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{